post_text:
The Red Oak High School Baseball Team and the Junior High Softball teams will be quarantined until September 2, 2020, due to a positive Covid-19 case on each of the teams.

Per the Latimer County Health Department, all of the quarantined students will now become medical virtual students according to the Red Oak Schools Covid-19 Policy. All assignments will be posted on Google Classroom.

Latimer County Health Department has begun contact tracing according to CDC guidelines and may be contacting the players and family members that have been in contact with a positive Covid-19 case.

During an interview with the LCHD on August 20, 202, it was determined that the seventh grade purple group had taken the necessary precautions through social distancing and sanitization, and will not be required to quarantine.

Any student under quarantine will not be allowed back on campus or to participate in any activity until September 2, 2020.

Dear Red Oak Family,

Unfortunately, we have a family that has had direct exposure to COVID-19. While they themselves have not tested positive, they have chosen to quarantine for 14 days for the safety of our students. Thank you,
Bryan Deatherage
Superintendent

post_text:
The Class of 2020 will graduate in an outdoor ceremony on Sunday at 3 pm in the parking lot of the high school gym...we are asking that parents and immediate family be allowed to park closest to the stage (which will be under the gym porch awning) with the general public parked further back in the lot.

After the ceremony concludes, we’re asking all those that can to completely line Main Street from the elementary school through downtown and cheer on our graduates as they make their way through our Graduate Parade! City police and fire will lead the way...we will live stream both the ceremony and the parade in order to give our graduates as much encouragement as we can. They have weathered this storm with exceptional attitudes and we want to properly welcome them into the annals of Eagle alumni!

Graduation: 3 pm
Parade: immediately following graduation
Those from the general public will exit the gym parking lot first in order to get their spots on the parade route and allow seniors/parents time to get in line behind city vehicles.

Today's Senior Spotlight is on Heather Truitt!

Heather is the daughter of Heath and Crystal Truitt and the granddaughter of Ronnie and Janice Owens and Minnie and Wayne Truitt and Kathie Truitt. She is the senior class historian and an FFA officer. In her time in the FFA chapter, she has been an important part of the Red Oak Show Team. After high school, she plans to attend EOSC and obtain a degree in agricultural education while competing as a member of the livestock judging team.

Today's Senior Spotlight is on Trista Ober!

Trista is the daughter of Tommy and Dusti Ober and in her four years at Red Oak she has won three state softball championships, a vital member of the Lady Eagle team all three years. She has served on the yearbook staff and has been indispensable to the senior breakfast crew. post_text:
Today’s Senior Spotlight is on Grace Montgomery!

Grace is the daughter of Johnny and Leigh Montgomery and is a valedictorian of the Class of 2020. She has been a member of the varsity fast pitch and slow pitch softball teams (winning three state championships and earning fast pitch All-State honors) a state basketball runner-up, an archery state champion, a member of the Red Oak FFA chapter, a member of the speech/drama team, and a charter member of the Red Oak NHS Chapter.

Grace has received numerous scholarships for her college education, including the Carloyn Watson Oppurtunities Scholarship ($12,000 per year for four years), the NSU President’s Leadership Class Scholarship, selection to the CASC Scholars Program, the Oklahoma Youth Expo Choctaw Nation Scholarship ($2500), and the Oklahoma Youth Expo Devon Energy ($1000).

Her plans are to attend NSU to pursue a Pre-Professional Health Degree with plans of becoming an optometrist.

post_text:
Today's Senior Spotlight is on Damien Holmes!

Damien, although fun-loving, ornery, and mischievous, is a very loyal young man who loves spending time with his family and friends. He is a very hard worker and can often be found fixing things up. Never idle, he ALWAYS has a project going. Damien has many interest, including hog hunting with his buddies, roping, and deer hunting.

Some of his favorite things are horses, Mexican food, and French onion dip (of which he has been seen buying in large quantities at a time). Damien was a member of the fall and spring state runner-up baseball team in 2016-17, a state runner-up in archery in 2017-18, and an archery state champion in 2019-20. He was a member of FFA all four years of high school and plans to continue his education next fall at Eastern Oklahoma State College.

post_text: Today’s Senior Spotlight is on Cadden Hardaway! Cadden is planning on attending KTC to obtain her phlebotomy certification and later the LPN program. “This quarantine hasn't really got her down too much,” her mom says, other than she can’t go out and eat or hang out with her friends. She enjoys binge-watching Netflix and working on her distance learning. “Cadden hasn't liked school from day one,” said mom, “and it has always been a chore to get her to go. Once in high school I'll never forget having to have Bob law escort her back to school because she decided to skip and go to the park, and I threatened to have him handcuff her the next time she was caught and bring her to her seat in class...I'm sure all her teachers know what I'm talking about when I say she was always late or always finding somewhere else to go. But she is truly gonna miss going to school and this isn’t how she pictured her senior year ending.”

Today begins our Senior Spotlight, honoring the Class of 2020!

Brayden Allen hasn’t let the quarantine get him down. From daylight to dusk, Brayden is on a pond or pit bank enjoying some fishing. A love of the outdoors is something he and his Pa David shared. He is a state champion member of the Eagle Archery team and a key leader on the team for four years. After high school, he’s headed to OSU Okmulgee to obtain his HVAC license. His favorite words of wisdom come from his dad: “It is what it is.”

post_text:
Coach Caldwell and the Red Oak basketball boys would like to close out their season with one last service project, and this one really hits close to home for them. A fellow teammate and friend, Dayton Crose, was diagnosed with scoliosis in January 2018. His condition has deteriorated and will require surgery on his spine in May at Shriners Hospital in Shreveport, Louisiana. While the length of his recovery is uncertain, we are hoping for a full recovery and return to basketball for his senior year.

We are asking each student Pre-K through seniors to donate $1, which Coach Caldwell and the basketball team will give to Shriners Hospital in honor of DT. Money will be collected by home room teachers, and Coach Caldwell will collect the donations on March 9.

Thank you for helping us show DT that we are supporting him. Our community always shows up big, so let's end this season the EAGLE WAY!

So what was that big announcement last week for students in grades 6-8?

Please join us on Tuesday, October 29, at 6 pm in the cafeteria for a 25-minute parent informational meeting!

A tour director will be there to meet you and explain more about this once-in-a-lifetime adventure to Washington, DC and Mt. Vernon during the summer of 2021. Contact Mr. White at kwhite@redoak.k12.ok.us with any questions.

Please consider joining us if you have any interest at all, as there will be FREE pizza! Don’t miss out!
